{"article_id":"V4uUyIluovGxf5S8","edus":[{"id":0,"text":"Florida voters during Tuesday ' s midterm elections approved Amendment 4 ,","depth":5},{"id":1,"text":"automatically restoring voting rights in the state for people","depth":6},{"id":2,"text":"previously convicted of felonies .","depth":6},{"id":3,"text":"Florida ' s Amendment 4 restores voting rights for people in the state","depth":8},{"id":4,"text":"convicted of felonies","depth":8},{"id":5,"text":"as long as they have completed their sentences ,","depth":7},{"id":6,"text":"although anyone","depth":8},{"id":7,"text":"convicted of murder or felony sex offenses","depth":8},{"id":8,"text":"would be excluded .","depth":7},{"id":9,"text":"Based on the Sentencing Project ' s 2016 estimates ,","depth":7},{"id":10,"text":"this benefits more than a million people .","depth":7},{"id":11,"text":"The organization estimated in 2016","depth":8},{"id":12,"text":"that nearly 1.5 million people in Florida have completed felony sentences","depth":10},{"id":13,"text":"but can ' t vote","depth":10},{"id":14,"text":"- about 9.2 percent of the voting-age population in Florida .","depth":9},{"id":15,"text":"The total , though , includes some people","depth":9},{"id":16,"text":"convicted of murder and felony sex offenses ,","depth":9},{"id":17,"text":"so not every one of those people benefits under Amendment 4 .","depth":8},{"id":18,"text":"Related","depth":3},{"id":19,"text":"4 winners and 2 losers from the 2018 midterm elections","depth":3},{"id":20,"text":"Black people ,","depth":7},{"id":21,"text":"who are disproportionately arrested and incarcerated ,","depth":7},{"id":22,"text":"will benefit the most .","depth":6},{"id":23,"text":"In 2016 , more than 418,000 black people out of a black voting-age population of more than 2.3 million , or 17.9 percent of potential black voters in Florida , had finished sentences","depth":7},{"id":24,"text":"but couldn ' t vote due to a felony record ,","depth":7},{"id":25,"text":"according to the Sentencing Project .","depth":7},{"id":26,"text":"( Again , this includes some people","depth":8},{"id":27,"text":"convicted of murders and felony sex offenses . )","depth":8},{"id":28,"text":"The amendment was officially supported by Floridians for a Fair Democracy ,","depth":6},{"id":29,"text":"which gathered more than 1.1 million petitions","depth":7},{"id":30,"text":"to put it on the ballot .","depth":7},{"id":31,"text":"It received bipartisan endorsements from the American Civil Liberties Union and the Koch brothers-backed Freedom Partners .","depth":5},{"id":32,"text":"Most states have at least some voting restrictions for people","depth":5},{"id":33,"text":"convicted of felonies .","depth":5},{"id":34,"text":"Most often , the law bars people","depth":7},{"id":35,"text":"who are currently in prison","depth":7},{"id":36,"text":"from voting .","depth":6},{"id":37,"text":"Some prohibit voting","depth":6},{"id":38,"text":"until a person finishes parole or probation , too .","depth":6},{"id":39,"text":"Florida , however , barred people from voting","depth":5},{"id":40,"text":"even after they ' ve completed their sentences .","depth":5},{"id":41,"text":"Only two other states","depth":7},{"id":42,"text":"- Kentucky and Iowa -","depth":7},{"id":43,"text":"currently do this .","depth":6},{"id":44,"text":"Virginia technically does under its Constitution ,","depth":7},{"id":45,"text":"but former Gov . Terry McAuliffe and current Gov . Ralph Northam , both Democrats , have used their executive powers","depth":8},{"id":46,"text":"to restore voting rights to those","depth":9},{"id":47,"text":"convicted of felonies .","depth":9},{"id":48,"text":"Only Maine and Vermont let people vote","depth":9},{"id":49,"text":"regardless of their criminal record ,","depth":9},{"id":50,"text":"which means","depth":9},{"id":51,"text":"that people in the two states can even vote from prison .","depth":9},{"id":52,"text":"Courts ,","depth":10},{"id":53,"text":"including the US Supreme Court ,","depth":10},{"id":54,"text":"have generally upheld such voting restrictions under the US Constitution ' s 14th Amendment ,","depth":9},{"id":55,"text":"which indicates","depth":9},{"id":56,"text":"that the government may abridge the right","depth":11},{"id":57,"text":"to vote","depth":11},{"id":58,"text":"due to \" participation in rebellion , or other crime . \"","depth":10},{"id":59,"text":"In Florida , there was a process in place","depth":5},{"id":60,"text":"for getting voting rights restored .","depth":5},{"id":61,"text":"But the process ,","depth":8},{"id":62,"text":"set up by Gov . Rick Scott","depth":9},{"id":63,"text":"( R ) ,","depth":9},{"id":64,"text":"was very arduous .","depth":7},{"id":65,"text":"It required people to wait as long as seven years","depth":9},{"id":66,"text":"to apply ,","depth":9},{"id":67,"text":"and the application review itself could take several additional years .","depth":8},{"id":68,"text":"Even after someone applied ,","depth":9},{"id":69,"text":"restoration of voting rights was far from guaranteed :","depth":9},{"id":70,"text":"According to the Florida Commission on Offender Review ,","depth":9},{"id":71,"text":"only 3,005 of more than 30,000 applicants had their voting rights restored through the system","depth":10},{"id":72,"text":"since Scott implemented it .","depth":10},{"id":73,"text":"As a result , Florida had disenfranchised more potential voters than any other state ,","depth":6},{"id":74,"text":"with more than 10 percent of all potential voters and more than 21 percent of potential black voters in Florida unable to vote due to felony records .","depth":6},{"id":75,"text":"With Amendment 4 ' s win on Tuesday , that will now change","depth":4},{"id":76,"text":"-","depth":5},{"id":77,"text":"and more than 1 million people will get back the right","depth":6},{"id":78,"text":"to vote .","depth":6}],"relations":[{"parent":157,"left":110,"right":156,"relation":"elaboration","nuclearity":"NS"},{"parent":110,"left":97,"ri